  - STATE_UPDATE: {'last_reflection_result': "## Post-Mortem Analysis Summary\n\n**Attempt 1, Round 1 - FAILED**\n\n### Solved Problems\nNone (first attempt - no fixes applied yet).\n\n### Unsolved Problems\n**Step 1 (Compilation) Failure**: The `go-118-fuzz-build` tool creates an overlay JSON file that replaces `testing/fuzz.go` to inject fuzzer support. However, Go 1.25.7 stores the standard library toolchain under `GOMODCACHE` (`/root/go/pkg/mod/golang.org/toolchain@v0.0.1-go1.25.7.linux-amd64/`), and Go 1.25+ explicitly **forbids overlay replacements under GOMODCACHE**.\n\n### Root Cause\nThe base image `gcr.io/oss-fuzz-base/base-builder-go@sha256:5d7001e7...` ships with Go 1.25.7, which uses the new Go toolchain management where the toolchain (including `testing/fuzz.go`) lives under `GOMODCACHE`. The `go-118-fuzz-build` tool (at `/tmp/go-118-fuzz-build/main.go:196`) hasn't been updated to handle this new toolchain location.\n\n### Recommended Fix Strategy\nOptions to resolve:\n1. **Pin Go version** in the Dockerfile to an older Go version (e.g., Go 1.23 or 1.24) that doesn't use GOMODCACHE for the toolchain\n2. **Set `GOTOOLCHAIN=local`** or similar environment variable to prevent Go from downloading a newer toolchain\n3. **Patch the build.sh** to set `GOTOOLCHAIN=go1.24` or similar before running `compile_native_go_fuzzer_v2`\n\n### Deterioration Score: **5/10**\nFirst attempt, build failed at Step 1 (compilation). No regression since there's no prior state.\n\n### Rollback Decision: **No**\nNone of the backtracking mechanisms apply (first attempt, no complexity overload, no logical loop, score ≤ 7)."}
